Published in Washington, D.C.            5am -- December 9, 1997            www.washtimes.com<br>
 <br>
War heroics exposed! Read all about it!<br>
Larry Lawrence was Bill Clinton's kind of hero. If you've got to go to war, Mr. Lawrence figured out the way to do it.<br>
By all accounts, his heroics in the Barents Sea were the stuff of legend: blown off the deck of the SS Horace Bushnell by a torpedo, adrift in icy water until rescued, getting his head back together (literally) over long months of recuperation, and then academic stardom at the University of Arizona.<br>
     The only trouble with all this is that Mr. Lawrence made it up. He was never aboard the Horace Bushnell, a merchant ship; he never felt a torpedo; he was never wounded; and he never graduated from the University of Arizona. Nevertheless, Bill Clinton gave him a grave among heroes at Arlington.<br>
     Well, why not? We live in a time when we must think of America as merely real estate, and facts are whatever it may be convenient to say they are. This is the legacy of Bill Clinton, who never met an inconvenient fact he couldn't rearrange. His White House does it all the time.<br>
     Mr. Lawrence is said to have assigned one of his wives -- he was only two shy of Henry VIII, so he was a veteran of many skirmishes if not a war -- to find a torpedoed ship he could say he served on. When she found the Horace Bushnell, and that it had been torpedoed &quot;on the Murmansk run,&quot; Mr. Lawrence couldn't believe that 40 years on someone would actually check it out. Certainly not the Clinton White House, which loathes military records.<br>
     He figured it would be safe to have come home to the University of Arizona, too, since it was out there in the desert where they probably didn't even know about records. He could always say a gila monster ate the transcript. Now the resurrection men will repay this heroism by digging him up for a second burial, and this time there will be no full military honors.<br>
     Mr. Lawrence, like little Billy Clinton of Hot Springs, knew how important it was to maintain his &quot;viability within the system,&quot; even if his idea of prestige was to be the ambassador to Switzerland. Hence the careless lies. But the Lawrence saga, sordid as it may be, leads us to a similar story of American valor, in the Vietnam War, a story to put Audie Murphy in the smokehouse. Why didn't Billy think of this years ago?<br>
     It's true that &quot;Bill Clinton&quot; did not serve in Vietnam, and that any one of several young men of Garland County could be said to have taken his bullet for him. But that is not the whole story.<br>
     Riven with guilt and shamed by his malingering, young &quot;Bill Clinton&quot; finally decided that he, too, must answer when country called. But he was determined to take no credit. Selflessness was an early boyhood trait. He would serve under an assumed name, a Sunday school boy who would be true to the spirit of the instructions Jesus gave to the rich man who, on begging to be a disciple of the Savior, was told to sell all his possessions and give the proceeds to the poor --anonymously, so he could not even receive their thanks.<br>
     Little Billy, with a name known but to God and the Marine Corps, was assigned to a sector west of Danang, almost within sight of Marble Mountain. One soggy summer's day, during a respite from the monsoon rains, he became separated from a patrol he was leading -- &quot;We came to a fork in the path and I took us to the right,&quot; he later told a court of inquiry, &quot;but I agreed with those who said we should have gone left.&quot; He wound up at nightfall lost and alone.<br>
     In the twilight haze, the young Marine officer mistook the young women of a rogue Cao Dai convent of the Wholly Reconfabulated Order of St. Peyronie for a Viet Cong mortar squad, surely an easy thing to do. With total regard for his own convenience and desperate to march toward the sound of the guns of his patrol, now engaged in a fierce firefight, he climbed the battlements of the convent and, under considerable resistance from the Mother Superior, fought his way in.<br>
     He suffered a severe head wound when the Mother Superior, knowing very well who he was and what he thought he was doing there, crept up from behind on little cat's feet and struck him a blow with a heavy No. 8 iron skillet. He was laid up for several hours. The novices of the convent nursed him back to health over this long convalescence, which he repaid by performing several exceedingly odd jobs.<br>
     For his services, the young novices awarded him the Distinguished Service Medal of St. Peyronie, with the admonition that he should repay their kindness to him on some distant day by bestowing the medal on a deserving young woman for a deed well done. That's all he was trying to do at the Excelsior Hotel. Paula Jones should salute him, not sue him.<br><br>
Wesley Pruden is editor in chief of The Times. <br>
